    options: ["Horizontal analysis", "Vertical analysis", "Ratio analysis", "All of the above"],
    correctAnswer: 3,
    explanation: "Horizontal, vertical, and ratio analyses are all types of financial statement analysis. Horizontal analysis (also called trend analysis) compares financial data over time to identify trends and patterns, typically expressing changes as percentages or absolute amounts. Vertical analysis expresses each item in a financial statement as a percentage of a base figure (e.g., total assets or total revenue), facilitating comparison of proportions within a single period. Ratio analysis uses financial ratios (such as liquidity, profitability, and leverage ratios) to evaluate various aspects of a company's financial performance and position. These analytical techniques are often used together to provide a comprehensive understanding of a company's financial health."
